tidyomics demo

2024-07-25

The aim of this analysis session will be to demonstrate how to use a new package, tidyomics, to streamline our Seurat code and make it easier for youse to manipulate single cell datasets.

Ive set up a new R library with tidyomics installed. Use the following parameters to start up an openondemand session:

Modules: RStudio-Server/2024.04.1+748-Java-11-R-4.4.0 R_LIBS_USER directory: /data/projects/punim1236/R_envs/R-4.4.0_tidyseurat Partition: interactive CPUs: 1 Memory: 40GB

Once the session is ready to go, import tidyomics.

There are two main advantages of the tidyomics package. The most obvious is that it allows us to pipe data from one function directly to another using a special operator, %>%. Instead of writing functions on consecutive lines and assigning separate outputs, we can simply chain them together.

Heres how you would create a fresh Seurat object of human splenic stromal cells without piping data:

spleen <- Read10X('/data/scratch/projects/punim1236/human_spleen_3/spleen_3/outs/filtered_feature_bc_matrix')
spleen <- CreateSeuratObject(spleen)

Using the pipe operator you can streamline those commands:

Read10X('/data/scratch/projects/punim1236/human_spleen_3/spleen_3/outs/filtered_feature_bc_matrix') %>%
  CreateSeuratObject() ->
  spleen

This is also useful when performing QC because it typically requires several functions to perform it completely.

spleen %>%
  mutate(percent.mt = PercentageFeatureSet(spleen, pattern = '^MT-')) %>% ## adds percent.mt column
  subset(subset = nFeature_RNA > 200 & nFeature_RNA < 6000 & percent.mt < 5) ->
  spleen

Say we want to visualise only a subset of the data without creating a copy of it or altering the original. The pipe operator helps here as well because we can pipe the output from the subset() function into any Seurat plot function, e.g.VlnPlot().

vlntheme <- list(
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(),
        axis.title = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.x = element_blank(),
        legend.position = 'none',
        line = element_line(colour = 'grey50'))
)

## original dataset
spleen %>%
  VlnPlot(features = 'CXCL13', pt.size = 0) + 
  vlntheme
## Warning: Default search for "data" layer in "RNA" assay yielded no results;
## utilizing "counts" layer instead.

## vs subsetted data, in a single function - we will remove cells expressing CCL21
spleen %>%
  NormalizeData() %>%
  subset(subset = rna_CCL21 == 0) %>% 
  VlnPlot(features = 'CXCL13', pt.size = 0) + 
  vlntheme
## Normalizing layer: counts

dimtheme <- list(
  coord_fixed(),
  theme(axis.text = element_blank(),
        axis.title = element_text(hjust=0.05, colour='grey30'),
        axis.ticks = element_blank(),
        legend.position = 'none',
        line = element_line(colour = 'grey50'))
)

  RunUMAP(dims = 1:10) %>%

Finally, you can also easily create new variables to plot or on which to subset without having to create save that variable to your Seurat object using the mutate() function. We can demonstrate this by creating and plotting a variable encoding which cells are positive for CXCL13.

spleen %>%
  mutate(tf_cxcl13 = FetchData(spleen, 'CXCL13') > 0) %>%
  DimPlot(group.by = 'tf_cxcl13', cols = c('grey85','red3')) + 
  dimtheme + theme(legend.position = 'right')

Finally, we can easily aggregate the data based on, say, hashtag ID and cluster for downstream analyses like pseudobulk DE.

spleen %>%
  mutate(groups = as.factor(FetchData(spleen, 'CXCL13') > 0)) %>%
  aggregate_cells(groups, assays = "RNA") ->
  spleen_agg
## Joining with `by = join_by(groups)`
